Here is how you fix the race condition in your handwritten code using a ReentrantLock.
The key change is inside the Display class. We add a lock and ensure the entire for loop inside the wish method is protected by a try-finally block.
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

class Display {
    // 1. Create the Lock instance
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void wish(String name) {
        // 2. Acquire the lock before starting the work
        lock.lock(); 
        
        try {
            // CRITICAL SECTION: Only one thread can be inside this loop at a time
            for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                System.out.print("Good Morning: ");
                try {
                    Thread.sleep(2000); 
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                    System.out.println("Thread interrupted");
                }
                System.out.println(name);
            }
        } finally {
            // 3. ALWAYS release the lock in a finally block
            lock.unlock(); 
        }
    }
}

class MyThread extends Thread {
    Display d;
    String name;

    MyThread(Display d, String name) {
        this.d = d;
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void run() {
        d.wish(name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Display d = new Display();

        // Both threads share the exact same Display instance 'd'
        MyThread t1 = new MyThread(d, "Dhoni");
        MyThread t2 = new MyThread(d, "Yuvraj");

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}

Why this fixes the problem:
 * The Bottleneck: When t1 (Dhoni) calls d.wish("Dhoni"), it hits lock.lock() and successfully grabs the key.
 * The Wait: A fraction of a second later, t2 (Yuvraj) calls d.wish("Yuvraj"). It hits lock.lock(), but because t1 has the key, t2 is forced to pause and wait at that exact line.
 * The Execution: t1 safely executes its entire loop, printing "Good Morning: Dhoni" 10 times, completely undisturbed, even while sleeping.
 * The Release: Once t1 finishes the loop, it hits lock.unlock() in the finally block.
 * The Hand-off: t2 immediately wakes up, grabs the key, and prints "Good Morning: Yuvraj" 10 times.
Expected Output
Instead of jumbled text, you will now see perfect, sequential order:
Good Morning: Dhoni
Good Morning: Dhoni
... (8 more times)
Good Morning: Yuvraj
Good Morning: Yuvraj
... (8 more times)

